<section
  id='case-studiobid'
  class='fullscreen-section'
  data-title='Case Study: StudioBid — Web Development | Katja Turnsek'
  data-description='Auction platform case study focused on JavaScript, Bootstrap, Sass, API integration, listings, bids, profiles, credits, authentication, and reusable UI states.'
  data-case='studiobid'
>
  <div class='rows'>
    <div class='row'>
      <h1>Web Development</h1>
      <h2>StudioBid - Auction House App</h2>

      <div class='tech-demo-wrapper'>
        <div class='tech-stack'><strong>Tools:</strong>
          JavaScript | Bootstrap | Sass | Noroff API</div>

        <!-- Reusable component: Demo Links -->
        <div class='demo-links' data-auto='demo' data-case='studiobid'></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <!-- Reusable component: Project Switcher -->
      <nav
        class='project-switcher'
        aria-label='StudioBid sections'
        data-auto='switcher'
        data-case='studiobid'
      ></nav>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <h3>Objective</h3>
      <p>
        To build a responsive
        <strong>auction platform</strong>
        where users can browse listings, place bids, manage profiles, and track credits through the
        <strong>Noroff Auction API</strong>. The focus was to create a larger JavaScript application
        with reusable structure, clear user flows, and stable UI states across multiple features.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <div class='case-study-columns'>
        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <div class='case-study-text'>
            <h3>Development Focus</h3>
            <ul class='bullet-list'>
              <li>
                Built a multi-page front-end app with
                <strong>vanilla JavaScript</strong>
                plus
                <strong>Bootstrap + Sass</strong>
                for a consistent UI system and responsive layout
              </li>
              <li>
                Integrated the
                <strong>Noroff Auction API</strong>
                for listings, bids, profiles, media, and credits, handling real, changing data
              </li>
              <li>
                Implemented complete
                <strong>authentication flows</strong>
                for registration, login, logout, persisted sessions, and protected user actions
              </li>
              <li>
                Designed and implemented key flows:
                <strong>create listing</strong>,
                <strong>browse and filter</strong>,
                <strong>view listing details</strong>, and
                <strong>place bids</strong>
              </li>
              <li>
                Focused on
                <strong>reliable UI state</strong>
                with loading, empty, and error states across pages and forms
              </li>
              <li>
                Added usability and accessibility details like clear hierarchy, form feedback, and
                keyboard-friendly interactions
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <figure class='case-study-item item-right'>
            <img
              class='thumb'
              src='{{base}}assets/images/site-studiobid-600.webp'
              data-src='site-studiobid-600.webp'
              alt='Screenshot of the StudioBid auction app showing the hero headline “Turn your studio into credit,” a search bar with sort dropdown, and a grid of auction listing cards with highest bid and time remaining.'
            />
            <figcaption class='work-caption'>StudioBid - Landing page with search, sorting, and
              auction listing cards</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <figure class='case-study-item item-left'>
            <img
              class='thumb'
              src='{{base}}assets/images/site-studiobid-code-600.webp'
              data-src='site-studiobid-code-600.webp'
              alt='Code editor screenshot showing the setFieldState form validation helper that finds an input and feedback element, clears validation classes, and applies valid or invalid styling with feedback text.'
            />
            <figcaption class='work-caption'>StudioBid - Reusable form validation helper with
              feedback messaging</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <div class='case-study-text'>
            <h3>Key Features</h3>
            <ul class='bullet-list-right'>
              <li>
                <strong>Browse listings</strong>
                with responsive cards, search, sorting, bid status, and time remaining
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Listing detail pages</strong>
                with media, bid history, current bid, and bidding interaction
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Create and manage listings</strong>
                with title, description, tags, media, and end date
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>User profiles</strong>
                with avatar, banner, credit visibility, and listing/bid overview
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Reusable UI helpers</strong>
                for form validation, feedback messaging, and API-driven states
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <h3>Reflection</h3>
      <p>
        StudioBid strengthened my ability to structure a larger front-end application with
        <strong>API-driven data, authentication, reusable UI patterns, and predictable state
          handling</strong>. It pushed me to think beyond individual pages and focus on how
        listings, bids, profiles, credits, and form feedback work together as one product.
      </p>
      <p>
        The project also gave me more confidence working with
        <strong>vanilla JavaScript, Bootstrap, Sass, and real API responses</strong>
        in a way that still feels custom, structured, and ready for continued improvement.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class='back-to-work-container'>
      <a
        href='{{base}}#work'
        class='label-link back-to-work-label'
        data-back
        data-back-fallback='{{base}}#work'
        aria-label='Go back'
      >
        <svg class='icon icon-18 arrow-icon' aria-hidden='true'><use href='#i-arrow-left' /></svg>
        <span class='label-text'>Back to Work</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>